Why should we create VPC?
With VPC, you can control inbound and outbound access to your resources in your own virtual private network and securely connect your data center to the AWS cloud, as well as VPCs in other AWS accounts.
Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) is probably one of the most used and famous services inside the Amazon Web Services suite. The reason is simple: this service is mostly related to the concepts of security in the cloud and access to our data inside a third-party data center, like the ones of Amazon.

What is the difference between user and IAM user?
When should you use AWS IAM roles vs. users? | TechTarget
An IAM user is an entity that represents a person or application that interacts with AWS. It has specific credentials and permissions attached to it, like roles, to control access. A user is made up of a name, password for the AWS Management Console and access keys to use with the API or CLI.

What is difference between IAM user and IAM group?
IAM user groups - AWS Identity and Access Management
An IAM user group is a collection of IAM users. User groups let you specify permissions for multiple users, which can make it easier to manage the permissions for those users. For example, you could have a user group called Admins and give that user group typical administrator permissions.

IAM Role:
An IAM role is a set of permissions that can be assumed by AWS resources or entities. Unlike users or groups, roles are not directly assigned to individuals. Instead, they are assumed by trusted entities, such as AWS services or external applications, to access other AWS resources securely. Roles are often used in scenarios like granting permissions to an EC2 instance or allowing an AWS Lambda function to access specific resources.


